<file path="CLAUDE.md">
  1: # CLAUDE.md
  2: 
  3: This file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.
  4: 
  5: ## Commands
  6: 
  7: ```bash
  8: npm run dev       # Start development server (Vite, hot reload)
  9: npm run build     # Production build → dist/
 10: npm run preview   # Preview production build locally
 11: ```
 12: 
 13: No test runner is configured. There is no lint script — the project uses plain JSX/JS with no TypeScript compilation.
 14: 
 15: ## Architecture
 16: 
 17: **Grimoire** is a local-first PWA for managing personal reference cards (wiki-style), with AI-powered scanning via the Claude API.
 18: 
 19: ### Data Flow
 20: 
 21: ```
 22: IndexedDB (Dexie, db.js)
 23:     ↓ loaded on startup
 24: React Context + Reducer (context.jsx)
 25:     ↓ consumed by all components
 26: Components (src/components/)
 27: ```
 28: 
 29: State lives entirely in `context.jsx` (reducer pattern). All DB writes go through context actions (`saveCard`, `addProfile`, etc.), which also handle auto-backup every 10 saves.
 30: 
 31: ### Key Files
 32: 
 33: - **`src/db.js`** — Dexie schema (`cards`, `profiles`, `tags`, `settings`, `backups`). Contains migration logic from old localStorage format and the built-in D&D 5e profile.
 34: - **`src/context.jsx`** — Single source of truth. Exposes state and action dispatchers via `useGrimoire()` hook.
 35: - **`src/api.js`** — Claude API integration. `parseCardImage()` sends a base64 image to `claude-sonnet-4-20250514` with a prompt built from the active profile's section definitions. Direct browser-side fetch (no backend proxy).
 36: - **`src/linking.js`** — Link markup: `[[cardId|display text]]`. Functions for parsing, segmenting, inserting, removing, and computing reverse links.
 37: - **`src/App.jsx`** — Tab-based navigation shell (Library, Scan, Tags, Profiles, Settings).
 38: 
 39: ### Profiles
 40: 
 41: Profiles define the card schema: each profile specifies which sections a card has, their types (key-value vs. free text), and AI scanning instructions. The D&D 5e profile is hardcoded in `db.js` and always available. Custom profiles are stored in IndexedDB.
 42: 
 43: ### Deployment
 44: 
 45: Vite base path is `/grimoire/` — all asset paths are relative to that subpath. PWA service worker auto-updates. App is designed for mobile-first use at max-width 480px.
 46: 
 47: ### Styling
 48: 
 49: CSS variables in `App.css` define the design system (dark theme, gold accent `#c29a3e`, Cinzel/Nunito Sans fonts). No CSS framework or preprocessor.
 50: 
 51: 
 52: ## Conventions
 53: 
 54: - Discuss architecture decisions before writing code
 55: - Deployed to GitHub Pages at https://paulsmith1232.github.io/grimoire/; repo is `paulsmith1232/grimoire`
 56: - Git uses a personal access token with the noreply email for privacy
 57: - After `npm run build`, the `dist/` output must be pushed to the deployment branch for changes to go live
 58: 
 59: ## Standing Instructions for Claude Code
 60: 
 61: ### Implementing Specs
 62: - Pending specs below are written during planning sessions on claude.ai. They represent finalized decisions — do not second-guess architectural choices marked with "Decision/Rationale" unless they conflict with existing code, in which case flag the conflict and ask before proceeding.
 63: - Follow the **Implementation Notes** section of each spec closely. It lists the files to modify, where new code hooks in, and what is explicitly out of scope.
 64: - If anything in a spec is genuinely ambiguous or impossible given the current codebase, stop and ask — do not silently deviate or invent an alternative approach.
 65: 
 66: ### After Completing a Spec
 67: - Move the completed spec from **Pending Specs** to **Ready for Testing**.
 68: - Add the implementation date and a summary of what was implemented, including any deviations.
 69: - Include a **Test checklist** — a short bullet list of the key behaviors to manually verify. Write these as user-facing actions, not implementation details. Think "what would I tap/see/check on the phone?" Each item should be a concrete action with an expected result.
 70: - Also append a new checklist entry to `src/qa-checklists.json` with a stable ID (kebab-case feature name + implementation date, e.g. `"profile-editing-2026-04-14"`). Mirror the test checklist items from CLAUDE.md into the JSON `items` array.
 71: - Example format:
 72:   ```
 73:   ### Feature: [Name] — Implemented 2026-04-14
 74:   [Implementation summary and deviation notes]
 75:   **Test checklist:**
 76:   - [ ] [Action] → [expected result]
 77:   - [ ] [Action] → [expected result]
 78:   **Deploy after testing:** `npm run deploy`
 79:   ```
 80: - Do NOT move specs directly to Completed. Only the developer moves specs from Ready for Testing to Completed after manual verification.
 81: 
 82: ### General
 83: - Do not modify or remove pending specs you are not actively implementing.
 84: - When making changes, keep commits granular — one feature or fix per commit with a clear message.
 85: - After any session where files were changed, do a final review pass to make sure no debug logging, commented-out code, or TODO placeholders were left behind.
 86: 
 87: ### Voice-to-Text Design Principles (apply to all new UI)
 88: 
 89: - All text inputs are multi-line auto-growing textareas. Min 2 rows, max 6 before scroll. 16px+ font size to prevent iOS zoom-on-focus.
 90: - Do NOT suppress autocorrect or spellcheck — voice dictation relies on these.
 91: - Large touch targets: all action buttons at least 44x44px.
 92: - No reliance on precise formatting in user input. All system prompts instruct Claude to handle voice-dictated, unpunctuated, conversational input.
 93: - Button-driven navigation. All major actions are initiated by taps, not typed commands.
 94: - Placeholder text in inputs should read like example voice dictation to guide users.
 95: 
 96: ### Cost Guardrails (apply to all Claude API interactions)
 97: 
 98: - After every Claude API response in chat or discovery flows, display a subtle line below the message: `~1,247 input tokens · ~384 output tokens`. Pull from the API response's `usage` object.
 99: - Before any batch API call where estimated input exceeds 30k tokens, show a confirmation dialog: "This will send approximately [N]k tokens to Claude. Continue?" Estimate with `JSON.stringify(payload).length / 4`.
100: 
101: ---
102: 
103: ## Pending Specs
104: 
105: ### Feature: Inline Card Linking
106: 
107: **Goal:** Any text within any card field can link to another card, Wikipedia-style. Tapping a link navigates to that card with full back-navigation support.
108: 
109: **Storage Format:**
110: - Inline tokens embedded in field value strings: `[[cardId|display text]]`
111: - `cardId` is the target card's unique ID (resilient to renames)
112: - `display text` is what renders visually
113: - Example field value: `"Deal [[abc123|Fire]] damage equal to your [[def456|Spellcasting Modifier]]"`
114: 
115: **Authoring UX:**
116: 1. User is editing a card field (any field)
117: 2. User selects/highlights a span of text
118: 3. A "Link" action appears (button or floating action)
119: 4. Tapping "Link" opens a card search/picker modal
120: 5. User selects the target card
121: 6. The selected text wraps in `[[targetId|selected text]]` in the raw field value
122: 
123: **Rendering:**
124: - In view mode (non-edit), parse `[[id|text]]` tokens in all field values
125: - Render linked text as styled tappable `<span>` elements — visually distinct with gold underline to match the grimoire theme
126: - In edit mode, show the raw `[[id|text]]` markup (no rendering of links)
127: 
128: **Navigation — Card History Stack:**
129: - Maintain an in-memory array of card IDs, capped at 10 entries
130: - When user taps a link: push target card ID onto the stack AND call `history.pushState({ cardId, depth })` on the browser History API
131: - Listen for `popstate` event — on back-swipe/back-button, navigate to the previous card in the stack instead of leaving the page
132: - **Sentinel behavior:** When the stack has only one entry (the first card opened from a list/search), the next back action exits card view entirely and returns to the previous screen. Use `{ root: true }` in the pushState data to distinguish "go back one card" from "exit card view entirely."
133: 
134: **Decisions:**
135: - Decision: Store link tokens as `[[cardId|displayText]]` directly in field value strings, not in a separate link table.
136:   Rationale: Survives card renames, no join overhead, keeps field values self-contained. Easy to debug by inspecting raw data.
137: - Decision: Use browser History API with a sentinel state, not a custom in-app router.
138:   Rationale: Hijacks mobile back-swipe naturally without fighting the browser. Sentinel pattern cleanly handles the "exit card view" vs "go back one card" distinction.
139: - Decision: Links render only in view mode. Edit mode shows raw `[[id|text]]` markup.
140:   Rationale: Keeps the editor simple. Users can see and manually adjust link tokens. A WYSIWYG editor would add significant complexity for minimal gain.
141: - Decision: Cap the history stack at 10 entries.
142:   Rationale: Prevents unbounded memory growth from deep link chains. 10 levels of depth is more than enough for practical use.
143: 
144: **Edge Cases:**
145: - Deleted target card: render the display text as plain (non-linked) text, or show a subtle "card not found" indicator (e.g., strikethrough or dimmed). Do not crash or show broken UI.
146: - Circular links (A→B→A): no special handling needed. The stack is linear history — user navigates back through it normally.
147: - Links created via API scanning: not in scope now, but the `[[id|text]]` format is compatible with future auto-linking where the scan prompt includes the card index.
148: - Empty display text: `[[id|]]` should not render a visible link. Treat as plain text (skip it).
149: 
150: **Implementation Notes:**
151: - Files to modify:
152:   - `src/linking.js` — already exists as a utility file. Add/update: `parseLinks(text)` returns array of `{ type: 'text'|'link', content, cardId? }` segments. Add `wrapLink(text, cardId)` for authoring. Add `resolveLinks(segments, cardLookup)` to check if target cards exist.
153:   - `src/components/LinkedText.jsx` — already exists. Update to render parsed segments as mixed `<span>` (plain) and tappable `<span>` (linked) elements. Receives an `onNavigate(cardId)` callback.
154:   - `src/components/CardDetail.jsx` — integrate `LinkedText` into field value rendering in view mode. Add the `popstate` listener and history stack management here (or in a custom `useCardHistory` hook).
155:   - `src/components/CardEditor.jsx` — add link authoring: detect text selection, show "Link" button, open card picker modal, wrap selection in `[[id|text]]`.
156: - New files:
157:   - `src/components/LinkPicker.jsx` — modal with search input that filters existing cards. Returns the selected card's ID. Keep it simple — a text input with a filtered list below it.
158:   - `src/hooks/useCardHistory.js` (optional) — encapsulate the history stack, `pushState`, and `popstate` listener. Cleaner than putting it all in CardDetail.
159: - The `popstate` listener must be set up carefully to not conflict with any existing navigation logic. Check what currently handles tab switching and card selection in `context.jsx` / `App.jsx` before wiring this in.
160: - Naming conventions: follow existing patterns — `useXxx` for hooks, `handleXxx` for event handlers, component files are PascalCase.
161: - Not in scope: auto-linking during API scanning, reverse link index ("what links to this card"), WYSIWYG link editing.
